<handout xml:id="handout-section-6-5-least-squares">
  <title>6.5 Least-Squares Problems</title>

  <page xml:id="p-6-5-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-6-5-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Least squares problems</li>
        <li>Methods for solving least squares problems</li>
      </ul>
      </objectives>

      <objectives workspace="0.2in">
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>Compute general solutions and least squares errors using both:
          <ul>
            <li>the normal equations</li>
            <li>the QR decomposition</li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      </objectives>

      <p><nbsp/></p>

      <definition xml:id="def-least-squares" workspace="0.2in">
      <title>Least Squares Solution</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix. A vector <m>\widehat x</m> is a
          <em>least squares solution</em> to <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> if
        </p>
        <me>
          \lVert\vec b - A\widehat x\rVert
          \le
          \lVert\vec b - A\vec x\rVert
          \quad \text{for all } \vec x\in\mathbb{R}^n.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>


    <note>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose <m>A \vec x = \vec b</m> is a <em>consistent</em> system.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Then there exists at least one vector <m>\vec v</m> so that <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            <m>A\vec v = \vec b</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                  
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      This vector <m>\widehat x =  \vec v</m> is a <em>least squares solution</em> to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> and we have that <me>\underline{\hspace{0.5in}} = \|\vec b - A\widehat\| \leq \|\vec b - A\vec x\|</me> for all <m>\vec x \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            <m>0</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                </ul>  
            </p>
            <p>
                Now, suppose  <m>A \vec x = \vec b</m> is an <em>inconsistent</em> system.
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Then there is no vector <m>\vec v</m> so that <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            <m>A\vec v = \vec b</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      So, a <em>least squares solution</em> <m>\widehat x</m> is a vector so that <m>A\widehat x</m> is <m>\underline{\hspace{3in}}</m> to <m>\vec b</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            as close as possible
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Recall that <m>A\vec x</m> is always a vector in <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            <m>\Col(A)</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      By <xref ref="thm-best-approx"/>, we have that <m>\widehat b = \underline{\hspace{2in}}</m> is the vector in <m>\Col(A)</m> that is as close as possible to <m>\vec b</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            <m>\proj_{\Col(A)}\vec b</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Thus, the <em>least squares solutions</em> to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> are the vectors <m>\widehat x</m> which are solutions to the equation <m>\underline{\hspace{1.5in}}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <answer>
                        <p>
                            <m>A\vec x = \widehat b = \proj_{\Col(A)}\vec b</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                  </li>
                </ul>     
            </p>
        </statement>
    </note>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-5-def-ls">
    <title>Least Squares Solution</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-5-inconsistent" >
      <introduction>
        <p>
            Consider the system <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> for <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \quad \text{and} \quad \vec b = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="2in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Is the system consistent?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Note that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp \rvert \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 11 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp \frac{1}{2} \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 11 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp \frac{1}{2} \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp \frac{21}{2}\end{bmatrix}</me>. Therefore, there is no solution and the system is inconsistent.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="6in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the vector <m>\widehat b = \proj_{\Col(A)}\vec b</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                In order to project onto <m>\Col(A)</m>, we need an orthogonal basis of <m>\Col(A)</m>. Since the columns of <m>A</m> are <em>not</em> orthogonal, we start by using the Gram-Schmidt Process. If we assign the columns of <m>A</m> as <m>\vec x_1</m> and <m>\vec x_2</m>, respectively, then we have that<md>
                    <mrow>\vec v_1 \amp = \vec x_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow> 
                    <mrow>\vec v_2 \amp = \vec x_2 - \proj_{\vec v_1}\vec x_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} - \dfrac{1}{17}\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = \dfrac{1}{17}\begin{bmatrix}-4 \\ 34 \\ 16\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                We will use <m>\vec v_2' = 17\vec v_2 = \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 34 \\ 16 \end{bmatrix}</m> in place of <m>\vec v_2</m>. So, <m>\left\{\vec v_1, \vec v_2'\right\}</m> is an orthogonal basis for <m>\Col(A).</m>. Therefore, we have that
                <md>
                    <mrow>\widehat b \amp = \proj_{\Col(A)}\vec b</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \proj_{\vec v_1}\vec b + \proj_{\vec v_2'}\vec b</mrow> 
                    <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{19}{17}\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + \dfrac{2}{17}\begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 34 \\ 16 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \dfrac{1}{17}\begin{bmatrix} 76 - 8 \\ 0 + 68 \\ 19 + 32 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 4 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                So, <m>\widehat b = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 4 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> is the vector in <m>\Col(A)</m> which is as close as possible to <m>\vec b</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="2in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the <em>least squares solution</em> to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We will solve the equation <m>A\vec x = \widehat b</m>. Note that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp \rvert \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Thus, the least-squares solution is <m>\widehat x = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Notice the error from our least-squares solution is <me>\|\vec b - A\widehat x\| = \|\vec b - \widehat b\| = \left\|\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 4 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}\right\| = \sqrt{4 + 16 + 64} = \sqrt{84}.</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-5-geometry">
    <note workspace="1in">
    <image xml:id="img-6-5-geometry" width = "60%">
      <latex-image>
        <latex>
\tdplotsetmaincoords{74}{20}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.4,
  axis/.style={->,black,-stealth}, 
  vectorY/.style={-stealth,DarkBlue,very thick},
  vectorH/.style={-stealth,black,very thick},
  vectorV/.style={-stealth,DarkRed,very thick},
  dsline/.style={black,dashed},
  perpline/.style={black, thin},
  tdplot_main_coords
  ]

  \coordinate (O) at (0,0,0);
  \coordinate (Y) at (1,0,1);
  \coordinate (H) at (1,0,0);
  \coordinate (V) at (1.2,1.3,0);
  \coordinate (C) at (-.3,-1,0);

  \filldraw[draw=DarkBlue!40,fill=DarkBlue!08]
    (-1,-1,0)--(2,-1,0)--(2,1.5,0)--(-1,1.5,0)--cycle;

  \draw[vectorY] (O)--(Y) node[above]{$\vec b$};
  \draw[vectorH] (O)--(H) node[below]{$A\widehat x$};
  \draw[vectorV] (O)--(V) node[below]{$A\vec x$};

  \draw[dsline] (Y)--(H);
  \draw[dsline,DarkRed] (Y)--(V);

  \draw[perpline] (0.85,0.0,0.15)--(1.00,0.0,0.15);
  \draw[perpline] (0.85,0.0,0.15)--(0.85,0.0,0.00);

  \draw (C) node[above]{Col$(A)$};
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex>
      </latex-image>
      <shortdescription>Geometric interpretation of least squares projection.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        The projection <m>A\widehat x</m> is the closest point in <m>\operatorname{Col}(A)</m>
        to the vector <m>\vec b</m>.
      </description>
    </image>

    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p> 
            Note that if <m>\widehat x</m> is a least squares solution to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m>, then <m>\vec b - A\widehat x</m> is orthogonal to every vector in <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m>.
          </p>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>\Col(A)</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p> 
            Then, we have that <m>\vec b - A\widehat x</m> lives in <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m>.
          </p>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>\Col(A)^\perp</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            By the <xref ref="thm-four-subspaces" text="custom">Four Subspace Theorem</xref>, we have that <m>\vec b - A\widehat x</m> lives in <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m>.
          </p>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>\Nul(A^T)</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p> 
            Therefore, we have that <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}\left(\vec b - A\widehat x\right) = \underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
          </p>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>A^T\left(\vec b - A\widehat x\right) = \vec 0</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            It follows that <m>\underline{\hspace{2in}}</m>.
          </p>
          <answer>
            <p>
              <m>A^TA\widehat x = A^T\vec b</m>
            </p>
          </answer>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </note>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-normal-equations" workspace="1in">
      <title>Normal Equations for Least Squares</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Least squares solutions of <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> are precisely the solutions of
        </p>
        <me>
          A^T A\vec x = A^T\vec b,
        </me>
        <p>
          refered to as the <em>normal equations</em>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-5-example-normal">
    <title>Example: Solving via Normal Equations</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-5-normal" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Use the normal equations to find the least-squares solution of <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>, where</p>
        <me>
          A=\begin{bmatrix}
            4 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 2\\
            1 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec b=\begin{bmatrix}
            2\\0\\11
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that <me>A^TA = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 17 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</me> and <me>A^T\vec b = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 19 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Therefore, then normal equations are <me>A^TA\widehat x = A^T\vec b \quad \implies \quad \begin{bmatrix} 17 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}\widehat x = \begin{bmatrix} 19 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Note that 
          <md>
            <mrow>\begin{bmatrix} 17 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 19 \\ 1 \amp 5 \amp \rvert \amp 11 \end{bmatrix} \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 5 \amp \rvert \amp 11 \\ 17 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 19 \end{bmatrix}</mrow> 
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 5 \amp \rvert \amp 11 \\ 0 \amp -84 \amp \rvert \amp -168 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 5 \amp \rvert \amp 11 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
          It follows that the least-squares solution is <m>\widehat x = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}</m>, which agrees with our answer from <xref ref="ex-6-5-inconsistent"/>.
          </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-5-unique-ls">
    <title>Conditions for Unique Least Squares Solutions</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ls-unique" workspace="0.5in">
      <title>Unique Least Squares Solutions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For an <m>m\times n</m> matrix <m>A</m>, the following are equivalent:
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li>For every <m>\vec b</m>, the equation <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> has a unique least squares solution.</li>
          <li>The columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.</li>
          <li><m>A^TA</m> is invertible.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          When these hold,
        </p>

        <me>
          \widehat x = (A^TA)^{-1}A^T\vec b.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-5-orth-cols" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute the least squares solution to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m>, where</p>
        <me>
          A=\begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -6\\
            1 \amp -2\\
            1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 7
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec b=\begin{bmatrix}
            -1\\2\\1\\6
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent, we know by <xref ref="thm-ls-unique"/> there is a unique least-squares solution to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m>. Note that the columns of <m>A</m> are already orthogonal. Therefore, this problem wouldn't be so bad to use our original method to finding a least-squares solution like in <xref ref="ex-6-5-inconsistent"/>. We will instead use the normal equations which is usually the fastest way, especially when the columns of <m>A</m> are <em>not</em> orthogonal.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note that <me>A^TA = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ -6 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -6 \\ 1 \amp -2 \\ 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 90 \end{bmatrix}</me> and <me>A^T\vec b = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ -6 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}-1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 8 \\ 45 \end{bmatrix}</me>. (The reason <m>A^TA</m> is diagonal is because the columns of <m>A</m> are orthogonal.) It follows that <me>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 8 \\ 0 \amp 90 \amp \rvert \amp 45 \end{bmatrix} \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp \frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix}</me>, so the least square solution is <me>\widehat x = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ \frac{1}{2}\end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-6-5-ls-qr" >
    <title>Least Squares Using QR</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ls-using-qr" workspace="0.5in">
      <title>Least Squares via QR Factorization</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A=QR</m> is a QR decomposition of an <m>m\times n</m> matrix <m>A</m>, then for
          any <m>\vec b</m> the least squares solution of <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m> satisfies:
        </p>

        <me>
          R\widehat x = Q^T\vec b.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex-6-5-qr-ls" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute the least squares solution to  <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>, where</p>

        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 3 \amp 5\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 2\\
            1 \amp 3 \amp 3
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec b=\begin{bmatrix}
            3\\5\\7\\-3
          \end{bmatrix}
        </me>

        <p>given the QR factorization:</p>

        <me>
          A = \dfrac{1}{2}
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp -1 \amp -1\\
            1 \amp -1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp -1
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 4 \amp 5\\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>

      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that we are given <me>Q = \tfrac12
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp -1 \amp -1\\
            1 \amp -1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp -1
          \end{bmatrix} \quad \text{and} \quad R = \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 4 \amp 5\\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}</me>. We have <me>Q^T\vec b = \dfrac{1}{2}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 5 \\ 7 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -6 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</me>. Therefore, by <xref ref="thm-ls-using-qr"/>, the least-squares solution to <m>A\vec x = \vec b</m> is the vector <m>\widehat x</m> so that <me>\begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 4 \amp 5\\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}\widehat x = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -6 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</me>. If <m>R</m> was a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix, then I usually find its inverse and multiply that to both sides. When <m>R</m> is <m>3 \times 3</m> or greater, then I usually solve it by Row Operations. Note that <md>
            <mrow> \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \amp 5 \amp \rvert \amp 6 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp \rvert \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp \rvert \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \amp 5 \amp \rvert \amp 6 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp \rvert \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp -4 \\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp -12 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp -4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 20 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \sim \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp 10 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp \rvert \amp -6 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \rvert \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
          Thus, the least-squares solution is <me>\widehat x = \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ -6 \\ 2\end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
  </page>


</handout>